Run CHUNK 2 to create a split box plot. For this I will select issue age (issage) as numeric variable and distribution channel (distchan) as categorical variable.

There does appears to be some sort of relationship. People who issue through channel B (bank/financial institutions) tend to be a little older.

Run CHUNK 3 to see what this looks like as stacked and split histograms.

# CHUNK 3
library(gridExtra)  #for gridArrange

## Stacked histogram
p1 <- ggplot(data = data.mortality, aes(issage, fill = distchan, 
    ..density..)) + geom_histogram(binwidth = 5, alpha = 0.5)

## Split histogram
p2 <- ggplot(data = data.mortality, aes(issage, fill = distchan, 
    ..density..)) + geom_histogram(binwidth = 5, alpha = 0.5, 
    position = "dodge")
grid.arrange(p1, p2, ncol = 1)

Nothing stands out, too much.

Distribution channel was kind of interesting. Lets seem if it has any relationships to any other categorical variables.

Run CHUNK 4 to build a stacked bar chart of distribution channel vs region.
# CHUNK 4
p1 <- ggplot(data = data.mortality, aes(x = distchan, fill = region)) + 
    geom_bar(stat = "count", alpha = 0.5)
p2 <- ggplot(data = data.mortality, aes(x = distchan, fill = region)) + 
    geom_bar(stat = "count", alpha = 0.5, position = "dodge")
grid.arrange(p1, p2, ncol = 2)

Interesting! It appears that for certain distribution channels (B,D => banks, direct), that region is not recorded. Also, looking at the dictionary there is mention of a code C for credit unions, but there is no data for that channel that Ive seen. Not sure if thats an error.

Double check.

Run CHUNK 4b for a pivot table.

# CHUNK 4b
library(reshape)
cast(data.mortality, distchan ~ region)

Thats the actual issue, the number of policies sold through those channels are dwarfed relative to A,I (affiliated and independent agents), that it appears that there are none or close to none on the bar charts.

So recalling the age vs distribution channel chart; the age distribution seemed to be different for D, but it could very well just be due to variance because of low credibility.

Run CHUNK 5 to see an example of a heat map. For this we will explore actual vs expected face value of claims.

Very trivial result; most of the concentration is in the lower left section. In other words, None or very little policies with very low expected face but high actual, or vice versa. But at least it agrees with what general intuition would be.
